10/21/22, 07:09 - N.Varalakshmi: // simple calculator 
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int a,b;
    printf("entera,b values:  ");
    scanf("%d,%d",&a,&b);
 int operation;
 printf("enter ur operation: ");
 scanf("%d",&operation);
 int sum;
    int sub;
    int multiple;
    int division;
    int modulo;
 switch (operation){
     case 1:
     sum = a+b;
     printf("sum is: %d\n",sum);
     break;
     case 2:
     sub = a-b;
     printf("sub is: %d\n",sub);
     break;
     case 3:
     multiple=a*b;
     printf("multiple is:  %d\n", multiple);
     break;
     case 4:
      division = a/b;
     printf("division is: %d\n", division);
     break;
     case 5:
      modulo = a%b;
     printf("modulo is: %d\n",modulo);
     break;
     default:
     printf("sorry we don't have that operation");
 }

    return 0;
}

        int max = 0;
        int sum = 0;

4/7/23, 16:51 - N.Varalakshmi: #include <stdio.h>
#include<math.h>
int main() {
   int choice,a,b;
   printf("choice 1=sum\nchoice 2=subtraction\nchoice 3multiplication\nchoice 4=division\n choice 5= power\nchoice 6=square root\n");
   scanf("%d",&choice);
   switch(choice)
   {
       case 1:
       printf("sum operation\n");
       scanf("%d%d",&a,&b);
       printf("%d",a+b);
       break;
       case 2:
       printf("Subtraction\n");
       scanf("%d%d",&a,&b);
       printf("%d",a-b);
       break;
       case 3:
       printf("multiplication\n");
       scanf("%d%d",&a,&b);
       printf("%d",a*b);
       break;
       case 4:
       printf("division\n");
       scanf("%d%d",&a,&b);
       printf("%f",a/b);
       break;
       case 5:
       printf("power\n");
       printf("a=const b=power");
       scanf("%d%d",&a,&b);
       printf("%d",pow(a,b));
       break;
       case 6:
       printf("square root");
       scanf("%d",&a);
       printf("%.3f",sqrt(a));
       break;
       
   }

    return 0;
}

    printf("enter ur num: \n");
    scanf("%d",&num);
    for(int i=0;i<=10;i++)
    {
        scanf("%d",&cnum);

        {
            printf("game done\n");
            break;
        }
         else if(num<cnum)
         {
             printf("number is too low\n");
             
         }
              else if(num>cnum)
              {
                 printf("number is too high\n");
                 
              }
                 else 
                 printf("num not found\n");
        }

    return 0;
}

void kelvin_to_centi(float a);
void centi_to_fahrenheit(float a);
void fahrenheit_to_centi(float a);
int main() {
 int a,choice;
 scanf("%d",&a);
 printf("enter choice\n");
 scanf("%d",&choice);
 switch(choice)
 {
     case 1: printf("kilometers to meters");
       km_to_m(a);
       break;
     case 2: printf("centigrade to kelvin");
       centi_to_kelvin(a);
       break;
     case 3: printf("Kelvin to centigrade");
         kelvin_to_centi(a);
         break;
     case 4: printf("centi to fahrenheit");
         centi_to_fahrenheit(a);
         break;
     case 5: printf("Fahrenheit to centi");
         fahrenheit_to_centi(a);
         break;
         default:
         printf("no such case found");
 }
    return 0;
}
void km_to_m(int a)
{
    printf("%d",(a*1000));
    return;
}
void centi_to_kelvin(float a)
{
    printf("%.3f",(a+273));
    return;
}
void kelvin_to_centi(float a)
{
    printf("%.3f",(a-273));
    return;
}
void centi_to_fahrenheit(float a)
{
    printf("%.3f",((9*a)/5)+32);
    return;
}
void fahrenheit_to_centi(float a)
{
    printf("%.3f",((a-32)*5/9));
    return;
}

# define PIN 3108
# define CURRENT_AMOUNT 2000
void deposit();
void withdrawal();
void Balance_enquiry (int *a);

int main() {
    int pin,choice;
    printf("welcome to yono SBI\n");
    printf("please enter ur atm card\n");
    printf("please enter ur PIN\n");
    scanf("%d",&pin);
    if(pin==PIN)
    {
        printf("please choose BANKING OPTION\n");
        printf("please choose TRANSACTION\n");
        printf("enter ur choice\n");
        printf("1.Deposit\n2.with drawal\n");
       scanf("%d",&choice);
       switch (choice)
       {
           case 1: deposit ();
                   break;
           case 2: withdrawal();
                   break;
       }
    }
       else
      printf ("invalid pin\n");
    return 0;
}
void deposit ()
{
    printf("pls  enteraccount\ncurrent\nsavings\n");
       printf("your transaction is being processed\n");
             printf("please enter money in available denominations of 1.100 2.200 3.500 4.2000\n ");
             printf("enter money\n");
             scanf("%d",&money);
             printf("press enter\n");
             printf("money in denomination \n");
             printf("enter key\n");
             scanf("%d",&key);
             switch(key)
             {
                 case 1: printf("money is in the form of 100's\n");
                 printf("%d*100= %d",money/100,money);
                 break;
                  case 2: printf("money is in the form of 200's\n");
                 printf("%d*100= %d",money/200,money);
                 break;
                  case 3: printf("money is in the form of 500's\n");
                 printf("%d*100= %d",money/500,money); 
                 break;
                   case 4: printf("money is in the form of 500's\n");
                 printf("%d*100= %d",money/2000,money);
                 break;
}
printf("enter\n");
printf("sucessful debited take ur receipt\n");
Total=CURRENT_AMOUNT+money;
Balance_enquiry(&Total);
return;
}
void withdrawal ()
{
    printf("please enteraccount\ncurrent\n savings account\n");
    printf("available denomination 100's and 500's only\n");
    printf("please enter amount\n");
    scanf("%d",&money);
    if(CURRENT_AMOUNT>money)
    {
    printf("enter key\n");
    switch (key)
    {
        case 1: printf("need 100's denomination\n");
              printf("%d*100=%d\n",money/100,money);
      case 2: printf("need 500's denomination\n");
              printf("%d*500=%d\n",money/500,money);
    }
    Total=CURRENT_AMOUNT-money;
    Balance_enquiry(&Total);
    }
    else
printf("insufficient balance\n");
    return;
}
void Balance_enquiry(int *a)
{
    printf("%d is current amount\n",*a);
    return;
}

4/18/23, 18:37 - Megha@sis: Write an 'C' program to find the number of happy numbers in the given Range.

A happy number is a number when sum of square of individual digits become 1 when the process in repeatedly performed

Sample :
19
1^2 + 9^2 = 82
8^2 + 2^2 = 68
6^2 + 8^2 = 100
1^2 + 0^2 + 0^2 = 1
Hence 19 is a Happy Number

Input:
start_num, end_num

2 <= start_num <= 10000

Output : One integer - the number of Happy Numbers in the range

};
int main()
{
    int k,total,need,n;
    scanf("%d",&n);
    struct menu s[n];

    for(int i=1;i<n;i++)
    {
     printf("items\n");
      scanf("%d%s%d",&s[i].roll,&s[i].name,&s[i].cost);

   printf("entrr ur menu\n");
    printf("enter need\n");
    scanf("%d",&need);

     for(int i=0;i<need;i++)

        scanf("%d",&k);
           printf("%d.%s----%d\n",s[k].roll,s[k].name,s[k].cost);
           total=total+s[k].cost;

    }

};
int main() {
    int n,k,c,l=0;
    printf("enter no of questions\n");
    scanf("%d",&n);
    struct quizz s[n];
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
    {
        printf("enter question\n");
        scanf("%s",&s[i].question);
      for(int i=0;i<4;i++)
      {
         printf("enter ur choice and option\n");
        scanf("%d%s",&s[i].choice,&s[i].option);
      }
  }
 printf("correct answers of quizz\n");
  for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
  {
      
     printf("insert ur correct option\n");
      scanf("%d",&k);
      s[i].choice=k;
  }
   for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
  { 
     printf("enter ur option\n");
      scanf("%d",&c);
        if(s[i].choice==c)
        {
        printf("your answer is correct\n");
        l=l+1;
      }
  }
printf("your score is %d\n",l);
    return 0;
}

4/23/23, 12:33 - N.Varalakshmi: #include <stdio.h>
struct quizz{
    char question [90];
    int choice;
    char option[80];
   
};
int main() {
    int n,k,c,l=0;
    printf("enter no of questions\n");
    scanf("%d",&n);
    struct quizz s[n];
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
    {
        printf("enter question\n");
        scanf("%s",&s[i].question);
      for(int i=0;i<4;i++)
      {
         printf("enter ur choice and option\n");
        scanf("%d%s",&s[i].choice,&s[i].option);
      }
  }
  printf("your options are \n");
  for(int i=0;i<4;i++)
      {
          printf("%d.%s\n",s[i].choice,s[i].option);
      }
 printf("correct answers of quizz\n");
  for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
  {
      
     printf("insert ur correct option\n");
      scanf("%d",&k);
      s[i].choice=k;
  }
   for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
  { 
     printf("enter ur option\n");
      scanf("%d",&c);
        if(s[i].choice==c)
        {
        printf("your answer is correct\n");
        l=l+1;
      }
  }
printf("your score is %d\n",l);
    return 0;
}

void order();
int main()
{
	int a;
	order();
	do{
		printf("\n\n\nWhat is on your mind-\n 1) Order more \n 2) exit\n\n");
		scanf("%d",&a);
		switch(a)
		 {
		  case 1:
		    order();
		    break;
		  default:
		  	printf("Have a nice Day");
		  	break;
		 }
	  } while(1);

}

{
	int a,qty,rate,total,item;
	
		printf(" \nWelcome to the Milk Stone Ice Creams\n\

		1) Vanilla	50/-\n\

int veg()
{
          printf("veg profile\n");
          printf("1.mutter paneer- chapathi\n3.veg-Biryani\n4.paneer biryani\n");
          scanf("%d",&choice);
          switch(choice)
          {
              case 1: printf("how many pieces\n");
                   scanf("%d",&piece);
              printf("Requested to add one more choice\n if u need add one more  press  continue for 1 else 2 for break\n ");
           scanf("%d",&l);
           if(l==1)
           {
       scanf("%d",&k);
       switch(k)
       {
           case 1: 
                   m=non_veg();
                   return((piece*150)+m);
                   break;
           case 2: 
                   m=icecream ();
                   return((piece*150)+m);
                   break;
           case 3:
                  m=softdrinks();
                  return ((piece*150)+m);
                  break;
       }
                   }
                   else
                   {
              return ((piece*150));
              break;
          }
          case 2:  printf("enter pieces\n");
          scanf("%d",&piece);
          printf("one or more choice press 1tomove other wis stop\n");
          scanf("%d",&l);
          if(l==1)
          {
              printf("1.non-veg\n2.icecream\n3.softdrinks\n");
              scanf("%d",&k);
              switch(k);
              {
                case 1: 
                m=non_veg();
                return(m+(piece*100));
                break;
                case 2:
                m=icecream ());
                return(m+(piece*100));
                break;
                case 3: 
                m=softdrinks());
                return(m+(piece*100));
                break;
              }
          }
          else
{
return (piece*100);
          break;
}

          case 3:
           printf("enter pieces\n");
          scanf("%d",&piece);
          printf("one or more choice press 1tomove other wis stop\n")

scanf("%d",&t);
while(t--)
{
    int num;
    scanf("%d",&num);
    do{
        num/=10;
        n++;
    }while(num!=0);
    k=pow(10,n);
    l=num%k;
    m=num/k;
}
printf("%d\n",l+m);
return 0;
}

5/7/23, 17:01 - Megha@sis: Write an 'C' program to find the number of happy numbers in the given Range.

A happy number is a number when sum of square of individual digits become 1 when the process in repeatedly performed

Sample :
19
1^2 + 9^2 = 82
8^2 + 2^2 = 68
6^2 + 8^2 = 100
1^2 + 0^2 + 0^2 = 1
Hence 19 is a Happy Number

Input:
start_num, end_num

2 <= start_num <= 10000

Output : One integer - the number of Happy Numbers in the range

5/26/23, 15:13 - Megha@sis: Write an 'C' program to find the number of happy numbers in the given Range.

A happy number is a number when sum of square of individual digits become 1 when the process in repeatedly performed

Sample :
19
1^2 + 9^2 = 82
8^2 + 2^2 = 68
6^2 + 8^2 = 100
1^2 + 0^2 + 0^2 = 1
Hence 19 is a Happy Number

Input:
start_num, end_num

2 <= start_num <= 10000

Output : One integer - the number of Happy Numbers in the range

5/31/23, 12:07 - Megha@sis: public class PasswordGenerator {
    public static int generatePassword(int input1, int input2, int input3, int input4, int input5) {
        int sumOfStableNumbers = 0;

        if (isStable(input1)) {
            sumOfStableNumbers += input1;
        }
        if (isStable(input2)) {
            sumOfStableNumbers += input2;
        }
        if (isStable(input3)) {
            sumOfStableNumbers += input3;
        }
        if (isStable(input4)) {
            sumOfStableNumbers += input4;
        }
        if (isStable(input5)) {
            sumOfStableNumbers += input5;
        }

        return sumOfStableNumbers;
    }

    private static boolean isStable(int number) {
        String strNumber = String.valueOf(number);
        int frequency = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < strNumber.length(); i++) {
            char digit = strNumber.charAt(i);
            if (digit != '0') {
                int count = countOccurrences(strNumber, digit);
                if (frequency == 0) {
                    frequency = count;
                } else if (frequency != count) {
                    return false;
                }
            }
        }

        return true;
    }

    private static int countOccurrences(String str, char target) {
        int count = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < str.length(); i++) {
            if (str.charAt(i) == target) {
                count++;
            }
        }
        return count;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int input1 = 12;
        int input2 = 1313;
        int input3 = 122;
        int input4 = 0;
        int input5 = 676;

        int password = generatePassword(input1, input2, input3, input4, input5);
        System.out.println("Password: " + password);
    }
}
5/31/23, 12:14 - Megha@sis: public class KeyFinder {
    public static int findKey(int input1, int input2, int input3) {
        int largestSum = getLargestDigit(input1) + getLargestDigit(input2) + getLargestDigit(input3);
        int smallestSum = getSmallestDigit(input1) + getSmallestDigit(input2) + getSmallestDigit(input3);
        return largestSum + smallestSum;
    }

    private static int getLargestDigit(int number) {
        int largestDigit = Integer.MIN_VALUE;
        number = Math.abs(number); // Consider the absolute value of the number

        while (number > 0) {
            int digit = number % 10;
            if (digit > largestDigit) {
                largestDigit = digit;
            }
            number /= 10;
        }

        return largestDigit;
    }

    private static int getSmallestDigit(int number) {
        int smallestDigit = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        number = Math.abs(number); // Consider the absolute value of the number

        while (number > 0) {
            int digit = number % 10;
            if (digit < smallestDigit) {
                smallestDigit = digit;
            }
            number /= 10;
        }

        return smallestDigit;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int input1 = 3521;
        int input2 = 2452;
        int input3 = 1352;

        int key = findKey(input1, input2, input3);
        System.out.println("Key: " + key);
    }
}

5/31/23, 12:22 - Megha@sis: public class PasswordGenerator {
    public static int generatePassword(int input1, int input2, int input3, int input4, int input5) {
        int sumOfStableNumbers = 0;

        if (isStable(input1)) {
            sumOfStableNumbers += input1;
        }
        if (isStable(input2)) {
            sumOfStableNumbers += input2;
        }
        if (isStable(input3)) {
            sumOfStableNumbers += input3;
        }
        if (isStable(input4)) {
            sumOfStableNumbers += input4;
        }
        if (isStable(input5)) {
            sumOfStableNumbers += input5;
        }

        return sumOfStableNumbers;
    }

    private static boolean isStable(int number) {
        String strNumber = String.valueOf(number);

        int[] digitFrequencies = new int[10]; // Array to store the frequency of each digit (0-9)

        for (int i = 0; i < strNumber.length(); i++) {
            char digit = strNumber.charAt(i);
            digitFrequencies[digit - '0']++;
        }

        int firstNonZeroFrequency = 0;
        boolean isFirstNonZeroFrequencySet = false;

        for (int frequency : digitFrequencies) {
            if (frequency != 0) {
                if (!isFirstNonZeroFrequencySet) {
                    firstNonZeroFrequency = frequency;
                    isFirstNonZeroFrequencySet = true;
                } else if (frequency != firstNonZeroFrequency) {
                    return false; // Frequency of a digit is different, the number is unstable
                }
            }
        }

        return true; // All digits have the same frequency, the number is stable
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int input1 = 12;
        int input2 = 1313;
        int input3 = 122;
        int input4 = 0;
        int input5 = 898;

        int password = generatePassword(input1, input2, input3, input4, input5);
        System.out.println("Password: " + password);
    }
}
5/31/23, 12:31 - N.Varalakshmi: public class PasswordGenerator {
    public static int generatePassword(int input1, int input2, int input3, int input4, int input5) {
        int sumOfStableNumbers = 0;

        if (isStable(input1)) {
            sumOfStableNumbers += input1;
        }
        if (isStable(input2)) {
            sumOfStableNumbers += input2;
        }
        if (isStable(input3)) {
            sumOfStableNumbers += input3;
        }
        if (isStable(input4)) {
            sumOfStableNumbers += input4;
        }
        if (isStable(input5)) {
            sumOfStableNumbers += input5;
        }

        return sumOfStableNumbers;
    }

    private static boolean isStable(int number) {
        String strNumber = String.valueOf(number);

        int[] digitFrequencies = new int[10]; // Array to store the frequency of each digit (0-9)

        for (int i = 0; i < strNumber.length(); i++) {
            char digit = strNumber.charAt(i);
            digitFrequencies[digit - '0']++;
        }

        int firstNonZeroFrequency = 0;
        boolean isFirstNonZeroFrequencySet = false;

        for (int frequency : digitFrequencies) {
            if (frequency != 0) {
                if (!isFirstNonZeroFrequencySet) {
                    firstNonZeroFrequency = frequency;
                    isFirstNonZeroFrequencySet = true;
                } else if (frequency != firstNonZeroFrequency) {
                    return false; // Frequency of a digit is different, the number is unstable
                }
            }
        }

        return true; // All digits have the same frequency, the number is stable
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int input1 = 12;
        int input2 = 1313;
        int input3 = 678;
        int input4 = 122;
        int input5 = 898;

        int password = generatePassword(input1, input2, input3, input4, input5);
        System.out.println("Password: " + password);
    }
}

6/9/23, 18:59 - Megha@sis: Human values play a significant role in the life and work of a professional engineer. They shape their decisions, guide their actions, and influence their interactions with colleagues, clients, and the broader society. Here are some examples illustrating the importance of human values for a professional engineer:

Integrity: Engineers are expected to uphold the highest standards of integrity and honesty in their work. This means being transparent about limitations, acknowledging mistakes, and avoiding conflicts of interest. For example, if an engineer discovers a flaw in a design that could compromise safety, it is their ethical responsibility to report it, even if it means delaying a project or incurring additional costs.

Responsibility: Professional engineers have a responsibility to protect public welfare and prioritize the safety, health, and well-being of individuals and communities. They must ensure that their designs and projects adhere to relevant codes, standards, and regulations. For instance, a civil engineer working on a bridge construction project must consider the environmental impact, long-term sustainability, and potential risks to nearby communities.

Collaboration: Engineers often work in multidisciplinary teams, requiring effective communication, cooperation, and respect for diverse perspectives. By embracing teamwork and collaboration, engineers can leverage their collective knowledge and skills to solve complex problems more effectively. For example, in the development of a new medical device, engineers from different specialties must collaborate closely to ensure the device meets the needs of patients while adhering to regulatory requirements.

Innovation with empathy: Engineers have the power to create transformative technologies and solutions. However, it is essential that they consider the broader societal impact of their innovations. Human values such as empathy and compassion help engineers understand and address the needs and concerns of end-users. For instance, when designing assistive technologies for people with disabilities, engineers need to prioritize inclusivity, usability, and accessibility to empower and enhance the lives of individuals with diverse abilities.

Environmental consciousness: With growing environmental challenges, engineers play a crucial role in developing sustainable solutions. Incorporating human values such as environmental stewardship and sustainability in engineering decisions can lead to greener and more efficient designs. For example, engineers involved in renewable energy projects prioritize minimizing carbon emissions and maximizing energy efficiency to mitigate climate change and promote a cleaner and healthier environment.

Ethical leadership: Professional engineers often find themselves in leadership roles, guiding teams and making critical decisions. Human values such as fairness, respect, and ethical conduct are vital for effective leadership. Engineers who lead with integrity inspire trust, foster a positive work culture, and ensure ethical practices throughout their organizations.

In summary, human values are integral to the professional conduct of engineers. Upholding integrity, embracing responsibility, fostering collaboration, considering societal impact, prioritizing sustainability, and practicing ethical leadership are all examples of how human values guide and shape the work of a professional engineer.

Coding questions 

1.
/*
case sensitive uppercase and lowercase are distinct

input : telegram
output : 6
explanation : t,l,g,r,a,m
*/
int NonRepeatingCharacter(string s){
    int answer;
    unordered_map<int,int> m;
    for(char c:s){
        m[c]++;
    }
    for(auto i:m){
        if(i.second==1){
            answer++;
        }
    }
    return answer;
}


2.
/*
input : 5 3 3
output : 24
explanation : sec=1 -> 5
              sec=2 -> 5+3
              sec=3 -> 5+3+3
              total=5+8+11=24
*/

int findEnergy(int initialEnergy,int rate,int time){
    int answer=initialEnergy*time;
    for(int i=1;i<time;i++){
        answer+=(rate*i);
    }
    return answer;
}

11/6/23, 12:07 - N.Varalakshmi: #include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int n,temp,count=0,result,k=0,value=0,s=0;
   scanf("%d",&n);
   temp=n;
   result=n;
   
  do{
       result=result/10;
       count++;
   }while(result!=0);
   for(int i=0;i<count;i++){
       temp=n%10;
       k=temp*temp+k;
       n=n/10;
   }
   printf("%d\n",k);
  int no=k;
  int num=k;
   if(k==1)
   printf("happynumber");
   else{
       do{
           k=k/10;
           value++;
       }while(k!=0);
       printf("%d\n",no);
       
       for(int i=0;i<value;i++){
           int tempo=no%10;
           if(tempo==0)
           {
               s++;
           int s=tempo*tempo+s;
           no=no/10;
           }
       }
       printf("%d",s);
       if(s==1)
       printf("happy num");
       else
       printf("not a happy num");
   }
    return 0;
}

11/6/23, 20:56 - N.Varalakshmi: #include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int n, temp, count = 0, result=0,k=0, value = 0, s = 0;
    scanf("%d", &n);
    temp = n;
    result = n;

    do {
        result = result / 10;
        count++;
    } while (result != 0);

    for (int i = 0; i < count; i++) {
        temp = n % 10;
        k = temp * temp + k;
        n = n / 10;
    }

    

    if (k == 1) {
        printf("happy number");
    } else {
        // Reinitialize variables for the second loop
        n= k;
        k = 0;

        do {
            int tempo = n% 10;
            k = tempo * tempo + k;
            n= n / 10;
        } while (n != 0);

        if (k == 1) {
            printf("happy number");
        } else {
            printf("not a happy number");
        }
    }
    return 0;
}

12/8/23, 20:06 - N.Varalakshmi: . What are the 5 hardest interview questions?
In an HR interview, the 5 hardest questions are:

Tell Me About Yourself
Tell me about a time you made a mistake and how you dealt with it
Describe a time you dealt with a difficult colleague and how did you resolve it?
Why are you leaving your current job? 
Why do you want this job?

What is the company culture like?
What are your expectations for this role?

11 Questions About Background And Experience
The interviewer may ask about your qualifications, the companies you have previously worked for and your accomplishments in those roles. Here are a few such questions you can expect during an Intel interview:

Why did you choose to pursue this field of work?
Explain your educational background and how it relates to this role.
Describe a project you have worked on that you are particularly proud of.
How do you handle challenging situations at work?
What do you know about this company, and how do you think your skills can contribute to its success?
How do you stay organised and manage your workload?
What motivated you to apply for this role?
Describe a time when you exceeded expectations in your internship.
What inspired you to pursue this career path?
Describe a situation when you overcame a challenge at work.
What do you see as your biggest career accomplishment?
Related: Interview Question: 'What Is Your Greatest Accomplishment?'
12 In-Depth Questions
Asking in-depth questions helps the interviewer understand how you might approach key tasks. Here are 13 examples of such questions:

How do you manage your time when working on multiple projects?
What kind of data structures have you used in previous projects?
What approach do you take when working on complex problems?
Can you describe a challenging project you worked on and how you overcame any obstacles?
What is your process for testing and debugging code?
What is your experience with unit testing?
Describe an instance when you explained a technical concept to a non-technical person.
What experience do you have with version control systems?
Explain the process you follow when debugging a program.
How do you ensure the security of your code?
What kind of design patterns do you use in your code?
Explain how you approach optimising the performance of a program.

Salesforce admin interview questions on experience and background
Salesforce admin interview questions can be about your experience and background, as the recruiting managers want to know if you have the required technical knowledge and the know-how necessary for the role. It also helps them understand your hard and soft skills and understanding of Salesforce and also see if you are a fit for the organisation. Some of these questions include:

How long are you working on Salesforce?
Do you have any training or certifications?
What do you think are the benefits of a career in Salesforce?
How did you address discrepancies with clients at your previous job?
How would you resolve communication issues with your colleagues?
The answers to these questions differ from candidate to candidate, as each person interviewing for the position may not have the same level of experience and qualifications. Once this is done and you pass to the next round, they may ask you detailed questions to test your technical and practical knowledge about Salesforce.

In-depth Salesforce interview questions with answers
In-depth or technical questions can range from your knowledge about Salesforce concepts to your regular duties as a Salesforce admin. The questions help analyse if you can successfully fulfil your responsibilities in the company. Here are common technical questions about Salesforce:

1. What is Salesforce and what are the duties of a Salesforce administrator?
Interviewers typically ask this question to gauge your understanding of Salesforce and your awareness about the responsibilities the position entails. It is essential to answer this question in a clear and concise manner, as it shows that you know your responsibilities and are familiar with Salesforce CRM software. Prepare an answer to this question that shows your proficiency with Salesforce.
12/8/23, 20:06 - N.Varalakshmi: 2. What is a CRM?
The interviewer may ask this question to understand if you know about CRM. As the knowledge of this topic is an integral part of your job description, you need to keep your answer focused on CRM and its different types. Depending on your answer, the interviewer can assess if you are the right candidate for the job.
12/8/23, 20:06 - N.Varalakshmi: 3. What is cloud computing? Talk about its different types.
Due to its relevance to Salesforce and multi-faceted usage benefits, cloud computing is common in several organisations. The interviewer may ask you this question to understand the depth of your knowledge about cloud computing topics necessary for the role. Answer this concisely and accurately and add your own experience of working with cloud-based software.
12/8/23, 20:06 - N.Varalakshmi: 1. How would you describe online coding to someone who knows nothing about coding?
Hiring managers may use this question to assess your proficiency in basic coding concepts and understanding of the subject. They want to understand how well you can communicate with individuals who may not be familiar with the concept. You can explain the elementary ideas in simple terms from your experience.
12/8/23, 20:06 - N.Varalakshmi: 2. What do you know about data structures?
This question helps recruiters understand your knowledge of data structures and their importance in performing operations on the stored data. In your response, you can try to explain the type of data structures and their importance in writing optimised code and designing algorithms to showcase your understanding.
12/8/23, 20:06 - N.Varalakshmi: 3. What is the difference between a linked list and an array?
Interviewers may ask this question to examine your knowledge of data management in a programming language. In your response, you can compare the linked list and array on different parameters like storage, size and memory.
12/8/23, 20:06 - N.Varalakshmi: 4. What is the difference between LIFO and FIFO approaches?
Coders or programmers might be required to design efficient databases to maintain financial records and inventories. Your interviewer may ask you to compare LIFO and FIFO approaches to evaluate your knowledge of database programming and data extraction to remove duplicate records from a program. You can highlight the main points of difference between LIFO and FIFO and describe their functions in a computer program.
12/8/23, 20:06 - N.Varalakshmi: 5. How does variable declaration affect memory?
Variable declarations are the preliminary steps coders use while creating a source code. Employers may ask this question to determine your in-depth knowledge of variable declaration and how it helps to store information in a computer program. Mention how the allocated memory depends on the variable's data type in your answer.
12/8/23, 20:06 - N.Varalakshmi: 6. How do you find the first non-repeated character from a string input in Java?
In JavaScript, a string is a sequence of more than one characters, which includes letters, numbers or symbols. The interviewers may want to examine your technical understanding of core topics in coding. You can answer by explaining the primary steps to separate the first non-repeated character in a string and continue to explain the further step.
12/8/23, 20:06 - N.Varalakshmi: 7. How can you check if strings contain digits?
Hiring managers might ask you to explain the process of checking if strings contain digits to evaluate your knowledge of using string algorithms to solve complex coding problems. In your answer, elaborate on how creating a frequency array helps analyse the string's variables.
12/8/23, 20:06 - N.Varalakshmi: 8. What is the difference between String, StringBuilder and StringBuffer in Java?
Coders extensively use the String class, while StringBuffer and StringBuilder provide ways to manipulate strings. Your hiring manager can ask about mutable and immutable classes and how such characteristics help make multiple modifications to string characters. Candidates can explain how these functions affect objects and their modification benefits.
12/8/23, 20:06 - N.Varalakshmi: 9. Explain the steps to the bubble sort algorithm.
The bubble sort algorithm swaps adjacent elements when found in the wrong order. Employers may check your knowledge of bubble sort algorithms and their significance when applying for relevant positions. For this question, you may focus on the functions of bubble sort and on how it helps coders.
12/8/23, 20:06 - N.Varalakshmi: 10. What do you mean by multithreading in Java?
Interviewers often ask this question to test your understanding of multithreading in programming. It helps them discover your ability to execute multiple program parts by creating a thread in Java. You can answer this question by defining a multithread, describing its uses and giving an example where we may apply a multithread.
12/8/23, 20:06 - N.Varalakshmi: 2. Why did you choose a career in desktop support?
Recruiters want to understand your deeper reasons and meaning behind choosing desktop support as your profession. This question aims to understand whether the attractive compensation plan motivated your decision or a genuine desire to help fix computer issues.
12/8/23, 20:06 - N.Varalakshmi: 3. Why are you interested in our company?
This question aims to address your interests in working with a specific company and recruiters ask this to analyse your sincerity and commitment towards their company over others. Show the hiring managers you understand and care about the company's vision, mission and objectives and how you can help it achieve its organisational goals.
12/8/23, 20:06 - N.Varalakshmi: 4. What is your troubleshooting process?
This is another commonly asked desktop support interview question, as your job involves helping employees solve their everyday IT and system problems. Your answer is required to reflect the common desktop problems that users face and the standard process you follow to identify and fix them quickly.

You can share your troubleshooting process by answering how you identify a desktop problem, your process of diagnosing the issue and your strategies to fix it using the most effective solution. You can highlight how your troubleshooting process is flexible and adaptable in many situations to let the recruiters know your abilities to solve problems in different scenarios.
12/8/23, 20:06 - N.Varalakshmi: 5. How do you start the OS in safe mode?
This technical question allows you to express your understanding of the Windows operating system (OS). Normally, you can explain the answer verbally, but your recruiter may ask you to show the process or write the steps on a piece of paper. Ensure that you write the complete answer in sequential steps. If you know many ways of starting the OS in safe mode, list all those in your answer.
12/8/23, 20:06 - N.Varalakshmi: 6. Briefly describe your understanding of the NTLDR error
This is another commonly asked technical question that aims to test your knowledge of computer networks. As a desktop support professional, you may already know about NTLDR, which is vital for loading the system OS. The NTLDR error pops up whenever a file is missing from the OS. You can answer this question by sharing your expertise in resolving this issue by copying the NTLDR file from the OS CD with the recruiter.
12/8/23, 20:06 - N.Varalakshmi: 7. Which is more important between technical knowledge and interpersonal skills?
A successful job role requires both technical expertise and getting along well with one's colleagues. To answer this question, describe the importance of both types of skills for a desktop support job and how they can boost your efficiency and productivity.

While answering, you can prioritise technical knowledge considering your job but give importance to interpersonal skills as well because being able to reassure someone after their system crashed right before an important project submission is a desirable trait and can increase your chances of getting hired.

    <script>
        function openForm(evt, formName) {
            var i, tabcontent, tablinks;
            tabcontent = document.getElementsByClassName("tabcontent");
            for (i = 0; i < tabcontent.length; i++) {
                tabcontent[i].style.display = "none";
            }
            tablinks = document.getElementsByClassName("tablinks");
            for (i = 0; i < tablinks.length; i++) {
                tablinks[i].className = tablinks[i].className.replace(" active", "");
            }
            document.getElementById(formName).style.display = "block";
            evt.currentTarget.className += " active";
        }
    </script>

</body>

<div class="content">
        
<h2><center>ADAPTIVES</center></h2>
<ul>
<li><b><i>Python</i></b></li><br>
<p><b>Why:</b> Python is the most widely used programming language in AIML due to its simplicity, readability, and a rich ecosystem of libraries.<br><br>
<b>What to Learn:</b>s
Basic syntax and data structures (lists, dictionaries, tuples).
Functions, modules, and packages.Object-oriented programming(OOP)</p><br><br>
<li><b><i>NumPy and Pandas </i></b></li><br>

<b>Why:</b> NumPy and Pandas are essential libraries for numerical computing and data manipulation in Python.<br><br>
<b>What to Learn:</b>
NumPy arrays and operations.
Data manipulation with Pandas DataFrames.<br><br>
<li><b><i>Matplotlib and seaborn </i></b></li><br><br>
<b>Why:</b> Visualization is crucial for understanding data and model performance.
<b>What to Learn:</b>
Basic SQL queries for data retrieval.
Database design principles.<br><br>
<li><b><i>SQL </i></b></li><br>

<b>Why: </b>Many AIML applications involve working with databases to extract, transform, and load data.<br><br>
<b>What to Learn:</b>
Basic SQL queries for data retrieval.
Database design principles.<br><br>
<li><b><i>GIT</i></b></li><br>

<b>Why:</b> Version control is essential for collaborative coding and tracking changes in projects.<br><br>
<b>What to Learn:</b>
Basic Git commands (commit, push, pull).
Branching and merging.<br><br>
<li><b><i>Jupyter Notebooks:
</i></b></li><br>


<b>Why: </b>Jupyter Notebooks are widely used for interactive and collaborative coding in data science.<br><br>
<b>What to Learn:</b> 

Creating and running Jupyter Notebooks.
Integrating code, visualizations, and text.<br><br>
<li><b><i>Linux Commands:</i></b></li><br>

<b>Why: </b>Many AIML systems run on Linux, and familiarity with command-line interfaces is valuable.<br><br>
<b>What to Learn:</b>
Basic command-line navigation and file manipulation.<br><br>
<li><b><i>Data Serialization Formats:
</i></b></li><br>
<b>Why: </b>Understanding serialization formats is crucial for data interchange.<br><br>
<b>What to Learn:</b>
JSON and XML for structured data.
Pickle for Python-specific serialization.<br><br>
<li><b><i>Web Development (Optional):

        <h2><center><b>INTRO</b></center></h2>
        <p>5G, or fifth-generation technology, represents the latest advancement in wireless communication. It promises significantly faster data speeds, lower latency, and increased capacity compared to its predecessor, 4G LTE. Key features include enhanced mobile broadband, massive machine-type communication, and ultra-reliable low-latency communication. 5G employs advanced technologies like millimeter-wave spectrum, massive MIMO (Multiple Input, Multiple Output), and network slicing to deliver improved connectivity for diverse applications, from augmented reality to the Internet of Things (IoT). This technology is poised to revolutionize various industries and pave the way for a more interconnected and technologically advanced future.

</p>

12/25/23, 21:44 - N.Varalakshmi: ChatGPT 3.5

User
b) Explain in detail about the meteorological factors influencing the air pollution.

ChatGPT
Meteorological factors play a crucial role in influencing air pollution levels. Some key factors include:

Temperature Inversion:

During temperature inversion, a layer of warm air traps cooler air near the ground, preventing the upward dispersion of pollutants.
This stagnant air can lead to the accumulation of pollutants, especially in urban areas.
Wind Speed and Direction:

Wind can disperse pollutants and improve air quality by diluting and carrying away contaminants.
However, low wind speeds may result in the stagnation of pollutants, while high winds can transport pollutants from one region to another.
Atmospheric Stability:

Stable atmospheric conditions, characterized by a lack of vertical air movement, can trap pollutants near the surface.
Unstable conditions, with strong vertical mixing, help disperse pollutants and enhance air quality.
Relative Humidity:

High humidity can contribute to the removal of certain pollutants through processes like rain or particle settling.
On the other hand, low humidity can lead to the formation of particulate matter and the accumulation of pollutants.
Solar Radiation:

Sunlight can trigger photochemical reactions, leading to the formation of ground-level ozone and other secondary pollutants.
Solar radiation also influences the rate of chemical reactions in the atmosphere.
Topography:

The geographical features of an area can influence air circulation patterns and the dispersion of pollutants.
Valleys and urban canyons may trap pollutants, while open areas with good ventilation may experience better air quality.
Precipitation:

Rainfall can effectively remove pollutants from the air by wet deposition.
However, in some cases, rain can also contribute to the formation of pollutants through washout of precursor gases.
Understanding these meteorological factors is essential for assessing and managing air quality, as they directly impact the dispersion, transformation, and removal of pollutants in the atmosphere.





Message ChatGPT‚Ä¶

ChatGPT can make mistakes. Consider checking important information.

1/18/24, 17:12 - N.Varalakshmi: def reverse_complement(dna_strand):
    complement_dict = {'A': 'T', 'T': 'A', 'C': 'G', 'G': 'C'}
    reversed_strand = dna_strand[::-1]
    complemented_strand = ''.join(complement_dict[base] for base in reversed_strand)
    return complemented_strand
s = "GTCAG"
result = reverse_complement(s)
print(result)
1/18/24, 17:15 - N.Varalakshmi: def fourth_bit(number):
    # Convert decimal to binary and remove the '0b' prefix
    binary_representation = bin(number)[2:]

    # If the binary representation is shorter than 4 bits, consider it as 0
    if len(binary_representation) < 4:
        return 0

    # Extract the 4th least significant bit from the right
    fourth_bit_value = int(binary_representation[-4])

    return fourth_bit_value
decimal_number = 23
result = fourth_bit(decimal_number)
print(result)
1/18/24, 17:18 - N.Varalakshmi: def reverseArray(arr):
    # Get the length of the array
    n = len(arr)
    
    # Use two pointers approach to swap elements from the beginning and end
    left, right = 0, n - 1
    
    while left < right:
        # Swap elements at the left and right indices
        arr[left], arr[right] = arr[right], arr[left]
        
        # Move the pointers towards the center
        left += 1
        right -= 1
    
    return arr
input_array = [1,3,1,7,9,6,5,2]
result = reverseArray(input_array)
print(result)
1/18/24, 19:45 - N.Varalakshmi: def getSeatsAllocation(arr):
    seat_allocation = []  # List to store the final seat allocation
    
    seat_occupancy = set()  # Set to keep track of occupied seats
    
    for person in arr:
        seat = person
        while seat in seat_occupancy:  # If seat is occupied, increment and try next seat
            seat += 1
        
        seat_allocation.append(seat)  # Allocate the seat to the person
        seat_occupancy.add(seat)  # Mark the seat as occupied
    
    return seat_allocation

# Sample Case 0
arr_0 = [1, 3, 3, 2, 2]
result_0 = getSeatsAllocation(arr_0)
print(result_0)

# Sample Case 1
arr_1 = [1, 1, 1, 1]
result_1 = getSeatsAllocation(arr_1)
print(result_1)

1/30/24, 21:51 - N.Varalakshmi: 1.Find the Number of 4-combinations of {‚àû. ùíÇ, ‚àû. ùíÉ, ‚àû. ùíÑ , ‚àû.ùíÖ, ‚àû. ùíÜ}

1/30/24, 21:57 - Megha@sis: The coefficient of \(x^5\) in the expansion \((a+bx+cx^2)^{10}\) can be found by considering the term that contributes to \(x^5\) in the expansion. In general, the term in the expansion is given by:

\[T_k = \binom{10}{k} a^{10-k} (bx)^k (cx^2)^{10-k}\]

For \(x^5\), you need the term with \(k = 5\):

\[T_5 = \binom{10}{5} a^5 (bx)^5 (cx^2)^5\]

Simplifying, this becomes:

\[T_5 = \binom{10}{5} a^5 b^5 c^5 x^5\]

Therefore, the coefficient of \(x^5\) is \(\binom{10}{5} a^5 b^5 c^5\).

4/10/24, 11:23 - N.Varalakshmi: import turtle
import random
import time

# creating screen
screen = turtle.Screen()
screen.title("SNAKE GAME")
screen.setup(width=700, height=700)
screen.tracer(0)
screen.bgcolor("#1d1d1d")

# creating border
turtle.speed(5)
turtle.pensize(4)
turtle.penup()
turtle.goto(-310, 250)
turtle.pendown()
turtle.color('red')
turtle.forward(600)
turtle.right(90)
turtle.forward(500)
turtle.right(90)
turtle.forward(600)
turtle.right(90)
turtle.forward(500)
turtle.penup()
turtle.hideturtle()

# score
score = 0
delay = 0.1

# snake
snake = turtle.Turtle()
snake.speed(0)
snake.shape("square")
snake.color("green")
snake.penup()
snake.goto(0, 0)
snake.direction = 'stop'

# food
fruit = turtle.Turtle()
fruit.speed(0)
fruit.shape("square")
fruit.color("white")
fruit.penup()
fruit.goto(30, 30)

old_fruit = []

# scoring
scoring = turtle.Turtle()
scoring.speed(0)
scoring.color("white")
scoring.penup()
scoring.hideturtle()
scoring.goto(0, 300)
scoring.write("Score: ", align="center", font=("Courier", 24, "bold"))

# defining movements
def snake_go_up():
    if snake.direction != "down":
        snake.direction = "up"

def snake_go_down():
    if snake.direction != "up":
        snake.direction = "down"

def snake_go_left():
    if snake.direction != "right":
        snake.direction = "left"

def snake_go_right():
    if snake.direction != "left":
        snake.direction = "right"

def snake_move():
    if snake.direction == "up":
        y = snake.ycor()
        snake.sety(y + 20)

    if snake.direction == "down":
        y = snake.ycor()
        snake.sety(y - 20)

    if snake.direction == "left":
        x = snake.xcor()  # Fixed xcor()
        snake.setx(x - 20)

    if snake.direction == "right":
        x = snake.xcor()  # Fixed xcor()
        snake.setx(x + 20)

# keyboard binding
screen.listen()
screen.onkeypress(snake_go_up, "Up")
screen.onkeypress(snake_go_down, "Down")
screen.onkeypress(snake_go_left, "Left")
screen.onkeypress(snake_go_right, "Right")

# main loop
while True:
    screen.update()
    # snake and fruit collision
    if snake.distance(fruit) < 20:
        x = random.randint(-298, 278)
        y = random.randint(-248, 248)
        fruit.goto(x, y)
        scoring.clear()
        score += 1
        scoring.write("Score: {}".format(score), align="center", font=("Courier", 24, "bold"))
        delay = 0.1
        # creating new foods
        new_fruit = turtle.Turtle()
        new_fruit.speed(0)
        new_fruit.shape("square")
        new_fruit.color("red")
        new_fruit.penup()
        old_fruit.append(new_fruit)
    # adding ball to snake
    for index in range(len(old_fruit) - 1, 0, -1):  # Fixed range
        a = old_fruit[index - 1].xcor()
        b = old_fruit[index - 1].ycor()
        old_fruit[index].goto(a, b)
    if len(old_fruit) > 0:
        a = snake.xcor()
        b = snake.ycor()
        old_fruit[0].goto(a, b)
    snake_move()
    # snake and border collision
    if snake.xcor() > 300 or snake.xcor() < -300 or snake.ycor() > 250 or snake.ycor() < -250:
        time.sleep(1)
        screen.clear()
        screen.bgcolor("turquoise")
        scoring.goto(0, 0)
        scoring.write("game over\n your score is {}".format(score), align="center", font=("Courier", 30, "bold"))
    # snake collision
    for food in old_fruit:
        if food.distance(snake) < 20:
            time.sleep(1)
            screen.clear()
            screen.bgcolor("turquoise")
            scoring.goto(0, 0)
            scoring.write("game over\n your score is {}".format(score), align="center", font=("Courier", 30, "bold"))
    time.sleep(delay)

4/28/24, 21:03 - N.Varalakshmi: import speech_recognition as aa
import pyttsx3
import pywhatkit
import datetime
import wikipedia
listener=aa.Recognizer()
machine=ptttxs3.init()
def talk(text):
        machine.say(text) 
machine.runAndWait()
def input_instruction():
    global instruction
    try:
       with aa.Microphone() as origin:
         print("listening")
         speech=listener.listen(origin)
         instruction=listener.recognize_goggle(speech)
         instruction=instruction.lower()
         if "speech" in instruction:
           instruction=instruction.replace('vara','')
         print(instruction)
    except:
        pass
    return instruction
def play_speech():
    instruction=input_instruction
    print(instruction)
    if "play" in instruction:
        song=instruction.replace('play',"")
        talk("playing"+song)
        pywhatkit.playonyt(song)
    elif 'time' in instruction:
        time=datetime.datetime.now().strftime('%I:%M%p')
        talk('current time'+time)
    elif 'date' in instruction:
        date=datetime.datetime.now().strftime('%d /%m /%Y')
        talk("Todays date"+date)
    elif 'how are you' in instruction:
        talk('I am fine,how about you')
    elif 'What is your name' in instruction:
        talk("I an vara, what can i do for you?")
    elif 'who is' in instruction:
        human=instruction.replace('who is','')
        info=wikipedia.summary(human,1)
        print(info)
        talk(info)
    else:
         talk('please repeat')
play_speech()

4/29/24, 21:43 - Megha@sis: import speech_recognition as aa
import pyttsx3
import pywhatkit
import datetime
import wikipedia

listener = aa.Recognizer()
machine = pyttsx3.init()

def talk(text):
    machine.say(text)
    machine.runAndWait()

def input_instruction():
    instruction = ""
    print(instruction)
    try:
        with aa.Microphone() as origin:
            print("listening")
            speech = listener.listen(origin)
            instruction = listener.recognize_google(speech)
            instruction = instruction.lower()
            if "speech" in instruction:
                instruction = instruction.replace('vara', '')
            print(instruction)
    except:
        pass
    return instruction

def play_speech():
    instruction = input_instruction()
    print(instruction)
    if "play" in instruction:
        song = instruction.replace('play', "")
        talk("playing" + song)
        pywhatkit.playonyt(song)
    elif "time" in instruction:
        time = datetime.datetime.now().strftime('%I:%M%p')
        talk('current time' + time)
    elif "date" in instruction:
        date = datetime.datetime.now().strftime('%d /%m /%Y')
        talk("Todays date" + date)
    elif "how are you" in instruction:
        talk('I am fine, how about you')
    elif "What is your name" in instruction:
        talk("I am vara, what can I do for you?")
    elif "who is" in instruction:
        human = instruction.replace('who is', '')
        info = wikipedia.summary(human, 1)
        print(info)
        talk(info)
    else:
       talk('please repeat')

play_speech()

6/17/24, 19:41 - Megha@sis: To replace the missing values in each column of a given DataFrame with the most frequent values present in that column, you can use the following Python code:

```python
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

# Sample DataFrame creation (based on the provided sample output)
data = {
    'ord_no': [70001.0, np.nan, 70002.0, 70004.0, np.nan, 70005.0, np.nan, 70010.0, 70003.0, 70012.0, np.nan, 70013.0],
    'purch_amt': [150.50, np.nan, 65.26, 110.50, 948.50, np.nan, 5760.00, 1983.43, np.nan, 250.45, 75.29, 3045.60],
    'sale_amt': [10.50, 20.65, np.nan, 11.50, 98.50, np.nan, 57.00, 19.43, np.nan, 25.45, 75.29, 35.60],
    'ord_date': ['2012-10-05', '2012-09-10', np.nan, '2012-08-17', '2012-09-10', '2012-07-27', '2012-09-10', '2012-10-10', '2012-10-10', '2012-06-27', '2012-08-17', '2012-04-25'],
    'customer_id': [3002, 3001, 3001, 3003, 3002, 3001, 3001, 3004, 3003, 3002, 3001, 3001],
    'salesman_id': [5002.0, 5003.0, 5001.0, np.nan, 5002.0, 5001.0, 5001.0, np.nan, 5003.0, 5002.0, 5003.0, np.nan]
}

df = pd.DataFrame(data)

# Function to replace missing values with the most frequent value in each column
def fill_missing_with_mode(df):
    for column in df.columns:
        most_frequent = df[column].mode()[0]
        df[column].fillna(most_frequent, inplace=True)
    return df

# Fill missing values
df_filled = fill_missing_with_mode(df)

# Print the result
print(df_filled)
```

Explanation:
1. **DataFrame Creation**: A DataFrame is created with the given sample data, including `np.nan` to represent missing values.
2. **Function Definition**: A function `fill_missing_with_mode` is defined to iterate over each column of the DataFrame and replace missing values with the most frequent value (mode) of that column.
3. **Filling Missing Values**: The function is applied to the DataFrame to fill in the missing values.
4. **Result Display**: The resulting DataFrame with missing values filled is printed.

6/17/24, 19:42 - Megha@sis: To replace the missing values in each column of a DataFrame with the most frequent values present in that column, follow these steps:

1. **Identify Missing Values**: Detect the missing values in each column of the DataFrame.
2. **Determine the Most Frequent Value**: For each column, calculate the mode (most frequent value).
3. **Replace Missing Values**: Substitute the missing values in each column with the corresponding most frequent value.
4. **In-place Modification**: Apply these changes directly to the DataFrame to ensure the missing values are replaced.

This method ensures that the DataFrame is complete without missing values by utilizing the most commonly occurring data points within each column.

  <h1>Student Grade Predictor</h1>
  <form id="gradeForm">
    <label for="Maths">Maths</label>
    <input type="number" id="Maths" name="Maths" min="0" max="100" required />
    
    <label for="Physics">Physics</label>
    <input type="number" id="Physics" name="Physics" min="0" max="100" required />
    
    <label for="Biology">Biology</label>
    <input type="number" id="Biology" name="Biology" min="0" max="100" required />
    
    <label for="Social">Social</label>
    <input type="number" id="Social" name="Social" min="0" max="100" required />
    
    <label for="Telugu">Telugu</label>
    <input type="number" id="Telugu" name="Telugu" min="0" max="100" required />
    
    <label for="Hindi">Hindi</label>
    <input type="number" id="Hindi" name="Hindi" min="0" max="100" required />
    
    <label for="English">English</label>
    <input type="number" id="English" name="English" min="0" max="100" required />
    
    <button type="submit">Predict Grade</button>
  </form>

  <div id="result"></div>

<script>
  const form = document.getElementById('gradeForm');
  const resultDiv = document.getElementById('result');

  form.addEventListener('submit', async (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();

    const data = {
      Maths: parseInt(form.Maths.value),
      Physics: parseInt(form.Physics.value),
      Biology: parseInt(form.Biology.value),
      Social: parseInt(form.Social.value),
      Telugu: parseInt(form.Telugu.value),
      Hindi: parseInt(form.Hindi.value),
      English: parseInt(form.English.value),
    };

    resultDiv.textContent = 'Predicting...';

    try {
      const response = await fetch('http://127.0.0.1:5000/predict', {
        method: 'POST',
        headers: {'Content-Type': 'application/json'},
        body: JSON.stringify(data),
      });

      const json = await response.json();
      resultDiv.textContent = `Predicted Grade: ${json.predicted_grade}`;
    } catch (error) {
      resultDiv.textContent = 'Error predicting grade. Make sure the server is running.';
    }
  });

  <script>
    const form = document.getElementById('gradeForm');
    const resultDiv = document.getElementById('result');

    form.addEventListener('submit', async (e) => {
      e.preventDefault();
      const data = {
        Maths: parseInt(form.Maths.value),
        Physics: parseInt(form.Physics.value),
        Biology: parseInt(form.Biology.value),
        Social: parseInt(form.Social.value),
        Telugu: parseInt(form.Telugu.value),
        Hindi: parseInt(form.Hindi.value),
        English: parseInt(form.English.value),
      };

      resultDiv.textContent = 'Predicting... üîÆ';
      resultDiv.classList.add('loading');

      try {
        const response = await fetch('http:                            
          method: 'POST',
          headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
          body: JSON.stringify(data),
        });
        const json = await response.json();
        resultDiv.textContent = `Predicted Grade: ${json.predicted_grade} üéâ`;
        resultDiv.classList.remove('loading');
        resultDiv.classList.add('success');
      } catch (error) {
        resultDiv.textContent = 'Error predicting grade üòû';
        resultDiv.classList.remove('loading');
        resultDiv.classList.add('error');
      }
    });
  </script>
</body>
</html>

import pandas as pd
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
import pickle

# Load dataset
df = pd.read_csv('student_grades_dataset.csv')  
# Dataset columns: Student_ID,Name,Maths,Physics,Biology,Social,Telugu,Hindi,English,Grade

# Prepare features and target
features = ['Maths', 'Physics', 'Biology', 'Social', 'Telugu', 'Hindi', 'English']
X = df[features]
y = df['Grade']

# Encode target labels
le = LabelEncoder()
y_encoded = le.fit_transform(y)

# Save label encoder for later use
with open('label_encoder.pkl', 'wb') as f:
    pickle.dump(le, f)

# Split data
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y_encoded, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Train model
model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

6/6/25, 23:22 - Megha@sis: import pandas as pd
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split, cross_val_score
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder, StandardScaler
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.svm import SVC
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
import pickle

# Load dataset
df = pd.read_csv('student_grades_dataset.csv')  

# Features and target
features = ['Maths', 'Physics', 'Biology', 'Social', 'Telugu', 'Hindi', 'English']
X = df[features]
y = df['Grade']

# Label encode target
le = LabelEncoder()
y_encoded = le.fit_transform(y)

# Save label encoder
with open('label_encoder.pkl', 'wb') as f:
    pickle.dump(le, f)

# Scale features
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# Save scaler
with open('scaler.pkl', 'wb') as f:
    pickle.dump(scaler, f)

# Train-test split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_scaled, y_encoded, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Model list
models = {
    "Random Forest": RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=200, max_depth=15, random_state=42),
    "Logistic Regression": LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000),
    "SVM (RBF kernel)": SVC(kernel='rbf', C=10, gamma=0.1),
    "KNN": KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=3)
}

# Train and evaluate all models
best_model = None
best_acc = 0
for name, model in models.items():
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    print(f"{name} Accuracy: {acc:.2f}")
    
    if acc > best_acc:
        best_acc = acc
        best_model = model

# Save best model
with open('best_model.pkl', 'wb') as f:
    pickle.dump(best_model, f)

print(f"\n‚úÖ Best Model: {type(best_model).__name__} with Accuracy: {best_acc:.2f}")
6/6/25, 23:24 - Megha@sis: import pandas as pd
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder, StandardScaler
from sklearn.svm import SVC
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
import pickle

# Load dataset
df = pd.read_csv('student_grades_dataset.csv')  
# Expected columns: Student_ID, Name, Maths, Physics, Biology, Social, Telugu, Hindi, English, Grade

# Select features and target
features = ['Maths', 'Physics', 'Biology', 'Social', 'Telugu', 'Hindi', 'English']
X = df[features]
y = df['Grade']

# Encode target labels
le = LabelEncoder()
y_encoded = le.fit_transform(y)

# Save label encoder
with open('label_encoder.pkl', 'wb') as f:
    pickle.dump(le, f)

# Scale features
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# Save scaler
with open('scaler.pkl', 'wb') as f:
    pickle.dump(scaler, f)

# Split dataset
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_scaled, y_encoded, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Train SVM classifier with RBF kernel
svm_model = SVC(kernel='rbf', C=10, gamma=0.1, probability=True, random_state=42)
svm_model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predict and evaluate
y_pred = svm_model.predict(X_test)
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
print(f"SVM Model Accuracy: {accuracy:.2f}")

# Save model
with open('svm_model.pkl', 'wb') as f:
    pickle.dump(svm_model, f)

<script>
  const form = document.getElementById('gradeForm');
  const resultDiv = document.getElementById('result');

  form.addEventListener('submit', async (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();

    const data = {
      Maths: parseInt(form.Maths.value),
      Physics: parseInt(form.Physics.value),
      Biology: parseInt(form.Biology.value),
      Social: parseInt(form.Social.value),
      Telugu: parseInt(form.Telugu.value),
      Hindi: parseInt(form.Hindi.value),
      English: parseInt(form.English.value),
    };

    resultDiv.textContent = 'Predicting...';

    try {
      const response = await fetch('http://127.0.0.1:5000/predict', {
        method: 'POST',
        headers: {'Content-Type': 'application/json'},
        body: JSON.stringify(data),
      });

      const json = await response.json();
      resultDiv.textContent = `Predicted Grade: ${json.predicted_grade}`;
    } catch (error) {
      resultDiv.textContent = 'Error predicting grade. Make sure the server is running.';
    }
  });
</script>
</body>
</html>

  <script>
    const form = document.getElementById('gradeForm');
    const resultDiv = document.getElementById('result');

    form.addEventListener('submit', async (e) => {
      e.preventDefault();

      const data = {
        Maths: parseInt(form.Maths.value),
        Physics: parseInt(form.Physics.value),
        Biology: parseInt(form.Biology.value),
        Social: parseInt(form.Social.value),
        Telugu: parseInt(form.Telugu.value),
        Hindi: parseInt(form.Hindi.value),
        English: parseInt(form.English.value),
      };

      resultDiv.classList.remove('error');
      resultDiv.textContent = 'üéØ Predicting...';

      try {
        const response = await fetch('http://127.0.0.1:5000/predict', {
          method: 'POST',
          headers: {'Content-Type': 'application/json'},
          body: JSON.stringify(data),
        });

        const json = await response.json();
        resultDiv.textContent = `‚úÖ Predicted Grade: ${json.predicted_grade}`;
      } catch (error) {
        resultDiv.classList.add('error');
        resultDiv.textContent = '‚ö†Ô∏è Error predicting grade. Make sure the server is running.';
      }
    });
  </script>

6/7/25, 16:32 - N.Varalakshmi: # training_model.py

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder, StandardScaler
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report, confusion_matrix
import pickle

# Load the dataset
df = pd.read_csv('student_grades_balanced_dataset.csv')

# Show first few rows for sanity check
print("Sample data:\n", df.head())

# Define feature columns and target column
subject_cols = ['Maths', 'Physics', 'Biology', 'Social', 'Telugu', 'Hindi', 'English']
target_col = 'Grade'

# 1Ô∏è‚É£ Force subject columns to numeric (handle invalid values like 'AB', 'NA', etc.)
for col in subject_cols:
    df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col], errors='coerce')

# 2Ô∏è‚É£ Fill missing values with 0 (you can choose mean/median if preferred)
df[subject_cols] = df[subject_cols].fillna(0)

# 3Ô∏è‚É£ Encode the target column (Grade: A1, A2, B, C, D, E, etc.)
label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
df[target_col] = label_encoder.fit_transform(df[target_col])

# Save label encoder for future use
with open('label_encoder.pkl', 'wb') as f:
    pickle.dump(label_encoder, f)

# 4Ô∏è‚É£ Split into X (features) and y (target)
X = df[subject_cols]
y = df[target_col]

# 5Ô∏è‚É£ Scale the features
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# Save scaler
with open('scaler.pkl', 'wb') as f:
    pickle.dump(scaler, f)

# 6Ô∏è‚É£ Split into training and testing sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X_scaled, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42, stratify=y
)

# 7Ô∏è‚É£ Define and train the model
model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Save the trained model
with open('student_grade_model.pkl', 'wb') as f:
    pickle.dump(model, f)

# 8Ô∏è‚É£ Evaluate the model
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
print(f"\nModel Accuracy: {accuracy * 100:.2f}%")

# Detailed classification report
print("\nClassification Report:")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred, target_names=label_encoder.classes_))

# Confusion matrix
print("\nConfusion Matrix:")
print(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred))

print("\nModel training complete. Model and artifacts saved.")
6/7/25, 16:51 - N.Varalakshmi: # training.py

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split, GridSearchCV
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder, StandardScaler
from sklearn.svm import SVC
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report
import pickle
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore")

# 1Ô∏è‚É£ Load dataset
df = pd.read_csv('student_grades_balanced_dataset.csv')

# 2Ô∏è‚É£ Define columns
subject_cols = ['Maths', 'Physics', 'Biology', 'Social', 'Telugu', 'Hindi', 'English']
target_col = 'Grade'

# 3Ô∏è‚É£ Convert subject columns to numeric with 'AB' -> -1
for col in subject_cols:
    df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col], errors='coerce')
    df[col] = df[col].fillna(-1)

# 4Ô∏è‚É£ Add adjusted columns (replace -1 with 0)
for col in subject_cols:
    df[f'{col}_adj'] = df[col].apply(lambda x: 0 if x == -1 else x)

# 5Ô∏è‚É£ Add IsAbsent columns
for col in subject_cols:
    df[f'IsAbsent_{col}'] = df[col].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == -1 else 0)

# 6Ô∏è‚É£ Encode target labels
label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
df[target_col] = label_encoder.fit_transform(df[target_col])

# 7Ô∏è‚É£ Prepare final feature columns
feature_cols = []

# Raw columns
feature_cols += subject_cols

# Adjusted columns
feature_cols += [f'{col}_adj' for col in subject_cols]

# IsAbsent columns
feature_cols += [f'IsAbsent_{col}' for col in subject_cols]

# 8Ô∏è‚É£ Prepare X and y
X = df[feature_cols]
y = df[target_col]

# 9Ô∏è‚É£ Scale features
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# Save the scaler
with open('scaler.pkl', 'wb') as f:
    pickle.dump(scaler, f)

# 10Ô∏è‚É£ Split data
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X_scaled, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42, stratify=y
)

# 11Ô∏è‚É£ SVM model + GridSearchCV
svm = SVC(probability=True)

# Parameter grid
param_grid = {
    'C': [0.1, 1, 10],
    'kernel': ['linear', 'rbf', 'poly'],
    'gamma': ['scale', 'auto', 0.1, 1]
}

# Grid search
grid_search = GridSearchCV(
    estimator=svm,
    param_grid=param_grid,
    cv=5,
    scoring='accuracy',
    n_jobs=-1,
    verbose=2
)

# 12Ô∏è‚É£ Train with grid search
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

# 13Ô∏è‚É£ Best model
best_svm = grid_search.best_estimator_
print("\nBest parameters for SVM:", grid_search.best_params_)

# 14Ô∏è‚É£ Evaluate on test set
y_pred = best_svm.predict(X_test)
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)

print(f"\nTuned SVM Accuracy: {accuracy * 100:.2f}%")
print("Classification Report:")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred, target_names=label_encoder.classes_))

# 15Ô∏è‚É£ Save the trained model
with open('svm_model.pkl', 'wb') as f:
    pickle.dump(best_svm, f)

# 16Ô∏è‚É£ Save the label encoder
with open('label_encoder.pkl', 'wb') as f:
    pickle.dump(label_encoder, f)

print("\n‚úÖ Training complete. Model saved as 'svm_model.pkl'. Scaler saved as 'scaler.pkl'. Label encoder saved as 'label_encoder.pkl'.")

based on this give tha flask python code and the html code with the styyling
6/7/25, 16:58 - Megha@sis: from flask import Flask, render_template, request
import numpy as np
import pickle

app = Flask(__name__)

# Load model, scaler, label encoder
with open('svm_model.pkl', 'rb') as f:
    model = pickle.load(f)

with open('scaler.pkl', 'rb') as f:
    scaler = pickle.load(f)

with open('label_encoder.pkl', 'rb') as f:
    label_encoder = pickle.load(f)

subject_cols = ['Maths', 'Physics', 'Biology', 'Social', 'Telugu', 'Hindi', 'English']

@app.route('/')
def home():
    return render_template('index.html')

@app.route('/predict', methods=['POST'])
def predict():
    try:
        inputs = []
        is_absent = []

        for col in subject_cols:
            val = request.form.get(col)
            if val.strip().lower() == 'ab' or val.strip() == '':
                inputs.append(-1)
                is_absent.append(1)
            else:
                mark = float(val)
                inputs.append(mark)
                is_absent.append(0)

        # Adjusted marks (replace -1 with 0)
        adjusted = [0 if x == -1 else x for x in inputs]

        final_features = np.array(inputs + adjusted + is_absent).reshape(1, -1)
        scaled = scaler.transform(final_features)
        pred = model.predict(scaled)
        grade = label_encoder.inverse_transform(pred)[0]

        return render_template('index.html', prediction=f"Predicted Grade: {grade}")

    except Exception as e:
        return render_template('index.html', prediction=f"Error: {str(e)}")

if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(debug=True) <This message was edited>

6/21/25, 22:39 - Megha@sis: Here‚Äôs a breakdown of the core aptitude and reasoning topics you should master to clear the screening/tests of most MNC recruitment drives:

1. Quantitative Aptitude  
   a. Number Systems  
     - Divisibility rules, LCM/GCD, parity (odd/even)  
   b. Arithmetic  
     - Percentages, Ratios & Proportions, Averages  
     - Profit & Loss, Discount  
     - Simple & Compound Interest  
     - Time, Speed & Distance (incl. trains, boats & streams)  
     - Time & Work (workers, pipes & cisterns)  
   c. Algebra  
     - Linear equations (one/two variables)  
     - Quadratic equations & inequalities  
   d. Geometry & Mensuration  
     - Triangles, circles, quadrilaterals, polygons  
     - Area & perimeter, volume & surface area (3D solids)  
   e. Modern Math & Misc.  
     - Permutations & Combinations  
     - Probability  
     - Sequence & Series (AP, GP, HP)  
     - Data Interpretation (tables, bar/line charts, pie charts)

2. Logical & Verbal Reasoning  
   a. Series & Pattern  
     - Numerical series, letter series, alphanumeric series  
   b. Analogies & Classification  
     - Word/picture analogies, odd-one-out  
   c. Coding‚ÄìDecoding  
     - Symbolic coding, letter shifting, matrix coding  
   d. Blood Relations & Family Tree  
   e. Direction Sense & Distance  
   f. Syllogisms  
     - Venn diagrams, set-based reasoning  
   g. Logical Deductions  
     - Statements & assumptions, statements & conclusions, arguments & courses of action  
   h. Seating Arrangements & Puzzles  
     - Linear, circular, rectangular arrangements; comparison puzzles  
   i. Data Sufficiency & Critical Reasoning  

3. Tips for Mastery  
   ‚Ä¢ Understand basics first‚Äîdon‚Äôt just memorize tricks.  
   ‚Ä¢ Practice timed quizzes: speed + accuracy is key in MNC tests.  
   ‚Ä¢ Analyze previous years‚Äô papers of target companies (e.g., TCS NQT, Infosys Springboard, Cognizant).  
   ‚Ä¢ Maintain a formula sheet for quick revision.  
   ‚Ä¢ Take mock tests under exam conditions; review every mistake.  

4. Recommended Resources  
   ‚Ä¢ Books: ‚ÄúHow to Prepare for Quantitative Aptitude‚Äù (R.S. Aggarwal), ‚ÄúA Modern Approach to Verbal & Non-Verbal Reasoning‚Äù (R.S. Aggarwal)  
   ‚Ä¢ Online portals: IndiaBix, FacePrep, PrepInsta, HackerRank (for timed logical puzzles)  
   ‚Ä¢ Mobile apps: Testbook, Oliveboard, Pocket Aptitude  

By systematically covering these topics, timing yourself, and analyzing your performance, you‚Äôll build the speed and accuracy that MNC aptitude tests demand. Good luck!

9/15/25, 23:01 - Megha@sis: def max_xor_buildings(heights):
    stack = []
    max_xor = 0
    
    for h in heights:
        # Compare with decreasing stack
        while stack and stack[-1] < h:
            max_xor = max(max_xor, stack[-1] ^ h)
            stack.pop()
        
        if stack:
            max_xor = max(max_xor, stack[-1] ^ h)
        
        stack.append(h)
    
    return max_xor


# Input handling
if __name__ == "__main__":
    n = int(input().strip())
    heights = list(map(int, input().split()))
    print(max_xor_buildings(heights))

9/15/25, 23:04 - Megha@sis: def max_xor_buildings(heights):
    n = len(heights)
    max_xor = 0
    stack = []

    for h in heights:
        # Pop smaller elements because we can jump to this h from them
        while stack and stack[-1] < h:
            max_xor = max(max_xor, stack[-1] ^ h)
            stack.pop()

        # If stack still has a taller building, we can jump from h to it later
        if stack:
            max_xor = max(max_xor, stack[-1] ^ h)

        stack.append(h)

    return max_xor


# Input handling
if __name__ == "__main__":
    n = int(input().strip())
    heights = list(map(int, input().split()))
    print(max_xor_buildings(heights))
9/15/25, 23:04 - Megha@sis: Idi
9/15/25, 23:05 - N.Varalakshmi: avvatla
9/15/25, 23:07 - Megha@sis: def max_xor_buildings(heights):
    n = len(heights)
    max_xor = 0
    stack = []

    for h in heights:
        # check all stack elements that can jump to this h
        for prev in stack:
            if prev < h:   # only smaller buildings can jump to h
                max_xor = max(max_xor, prev ^ h)

        stack.append(h)

    return max_xor


# --------------------
# Input / Output
# --------------------
if __name__ == "__main__":
    n = int(input().strip())
    heights = list(map(int, input().split()))
    print(max_xor_buildings(heights))
